.\" See `man mdoc` for file format documentation
.Dd __BUILD_DATE__
.Dt WEB-LISTENER 1
.Os
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh NAME
.Nm web-listener
.Nd launch one or more local HTTP servers
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.de args
.Oo
.Op Fl -dir
.Ar directory
|
.Fl -config-file Ar config-json-path
|
.Fl -config-json Ar config-json-document
.Oc
.Op options
..
.Nm
.args
.Nm npx Nm
.args
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
program starts a Node.js HTTP/1.1 server listening on a requested port
.Pq "or multiple servers on multiple ports" ,
serving files from the given
.Ar directory ,
static fixtures, proxying to another server, and/or redirecting requests.
It also has limited support for launching background tasks
.Pq "e.g. for transpiling source code" .
.Pp
Simple servers can be configured using commandline arguments, but more complex
setups require the use of JSON configuration.
It is possible to combine most arguments with JSON configuration, in which case
the commandline arguments will override the relevant parts of the JSON.
.Pp
Once running, the server(s) can be closed cleanly by sending a single SIGINT
.Pq "typically by pressing Ctrl+C in most terminals" .
.Pp
.Qq index.htm
and
.Qq index.html
are automatically recognised as index files for directories.
.Pp
.de compression
Allow clients to negotiate \\$1 compression.
Will look for files ending
.Qq \\$2
to serve for these requests
.Pq "content will not be dynamically compressed" .
Set
.Fl -write-compressed
to automatically generate these files at startup.
..
.de nojson
This cannot be combined with JSON configuration
.Po
.Fl -config-json
or
.Fl -config-file
.Pc .
..
The options are as follows:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.
.It Fl -404 Ar file
Path to a file
.Po
relative to
.Fl -dir
.Pc
to serve with a HTTP 404 status code if a requested file is not found.
.nojson
If you want to serve the file with a HTTP 200 status code, use
.Fl -spa
instead.
.
.It Fl a Ar address , Fl -host Ar address
The address to bind to.
Defaults to
.Qq localhost
.Pq "i.e. only available on the local machine" .
Use
.Qq 0.0.0.0
to listen on all addresses
.Pq "i.e. be available over all networks" .
If used with JSON configuration, this will override the host for all configured
servers.
.
.It Fl b , Fl -br , Fl -brotli
.compression Brotli .br
.
.It Fl C Ar document , Fl -config-json Ar document
An inline JSON configuration document specifying more advanced configuration.
See
.Sx JSON CONFIGURATION
below for details on the format.
.
.It Fl c Ar path , Fl -config-file Ar path
A path
.Pq relative to the current working directory
to a JSON configuration document.
See
.Sx JSON CONFIGURATION
below for details on the format.
When JSON is provided this way, paths in the document are resolved relative to
the file, not the current working directory.
Once running, the configuration can be reloaded by sending SIGHUP, or by
providing a newline to stdin.
.
.It Fl d Ar directory , Fl -dir Ar directory
The directory to serve files from, relative to the current working directory.
Defaults to
.Qq "." .
.nojson
.
.It Fl -deflate
.compression Deflate .deflate
.
.It Fl -exec Ar command
Execute a command as a background task.
Can be specified multiple times to run multiple background tasks.
The command will be split into arguments at each space, for example to run the
TypeScript compiler in watch mode:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --exec 'tsc -w'"
.
.It Fl e , Fl -ext
A file extension which should be considered
.Qq "implicit" .
This can be provided multiple times to register multiple implicit file
extensions.
If a user requests a file which does not exist, the implicit file extensions
are checked to see if a matching file can be found.
If found, the file is sent as a direct response to the user
.Pq "i.e. the user is not issued a redirect" .
.
.It Fl g , Fl -gz , Fl -gzip
.compression Gzip .gz
.
.It Fl H Ar name : Ns Ar value , Fl -header Ar name : Ns Ar value
Set a header key/value pair on all file and proxy responses.
This can be specified multiple times to set multiple headers
.Pq "or the same header multiple times" .
.
.It Fl h , Fl -help
Open this man page.
.
.It Fl -log Cm none | ready | progress | full
Logging verbosity.
Defaults to
.Qq "full" .
.Bl -tag -width "progress"
.It Cm none
Print nothing except errors.
.It Cm ready
Print errors, and
.Qq all servers ready
line once all servers have started successfully.
.It Cm progress
Print everything from
.Cm ready
and also startup, reload, and shutdown progress messages for each server.
.It Cm full
Print everything from
.Cm progress
and also a line for each requested resource, showing the status code and
processing time.
.El
.
.It Fl -mime Ar mapping
Add additional mime mapping(s).
.Ar mapping
takes the form of
.Qq "foo=application/foo" .
This can be provided multiple times to register additional mappings, and
multiple mappings can be defined in a single argument by using
.Qq ";"
or newline separators.
See
.Sx MIME DEFINITIONS
below for more details on specifying mime type mappings.
.
.It Fl -mime-types Ar path
Add additional mime mappings from an Apache .types formatted file.
An example of this format can be found at
.Lk https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/httpd/httpd/trunk/docs/conf/mime.types .
.
.It Fl -min-compress
The minimum compression
.Pq in bytes
which must be achieved when using
.Fl -write-compressed .
Defaults to
.Qq 300 .
If this amount of compression is not achieved, the compressed file is discarded
without saving.
.
.It Fl -no-serve
Do not start the server(s); just validate the configuration and generate
compressed files if requested
.Po
via the
.Fl -write-compressed
flag
.Pc ,
then exit successfully.
.
.It Fl P Ar proxy , Fl -proxy Ar proxy
A server to proxy requests to which do not match any files in
.Ar directory .
.nojson
Note that if
.Fl -404
or
.Fl -spa
are set, this will have no effect.
.
.It Fl p Ar port , Fl -port Ar port
The port to listen on.
Defaults to
.Qq "8080" .
This can be combined with JSON configuration provided only a single server is
defined.
.
.It Fl -spa Ar file
Path to a file
.Po
relative to
.Fl -dir
.Pc
to serve with a HTTP 200 status code if a requested file is not found.
This is typically useful for
.Qq "single-page"
apps.
.nojson
If you want to serve the file with a HTTP 404 status code, use
.Fl -404
instead.
.
.It Fl v , Fl -version
Print version information and exit.
.
.It Fl -write-compressed
Generate and save compressed versions of all files in
.Fl -dir
.Pq and sub-directories
at startup.
The type of compression used depends on the
.Fl -brotli ,
.Fl -deflate ,
.Fl -gzip ,
and
.Fl -zstd
flags.
If used with JSON configuration, this will generate the relevant compressed
files for each configured
.Qq files
section individually.
.
.It Fl -zst , Fl -zstd
.compression Zstd .zstd
.
.El
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width "NO_COLOR"
.
.It Ev NO_COLOR
If set, the output will not include any ANSI escape sequences.
.
.El
.Pp
Other environment variables are processed by the
.Xr node 1
executable.
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh JSON CONFIGURATION
JSON offers a more powerful way to configure the server, as well
as allowing multiple servers to be launched by a single
.Nm
process.
You can define one or more servers
.Pq "one per port" ,
each with its own set of mounted handlers.
Most commandline arguments can be specified alongside JSON configuration, with
the commandline arguments replacing the relevant options.
.Pp
For details on the JSON format itself, see
.Lk https://www.json.org/json-en.html .
.Pp
Minimal configuration to serve files from the current directory:
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "servers": [
    { "port": 8080, "mount": [{ "type": "files", "dir": "." }] }
  ]
}
.Ed
.Pp
More complex example definition, serving files if available, a
static fixture for
.Qq "hello.txt" ,
redirecting
.Qq "*.php"
requests to
.Qq "*.new" ,
proxying all non-matching requests to
.Qq "https://example.com" ,
running the TypeScript compiler in the background, and registering the
.Qq "application/x-foo"
mime type for
.Qq "*.foo"
files:
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "servers": [
    {
      "port": 9000,
      "mount": [
        { "type": "files", "dir": "." },
        { "type": "fixture", "method": "GET", "path": "/hello.txt", "body": "Hi!" },
        { "type": "redirect", "path": "/*thepath.php", "target": "/${thepath}.new${?}" },
        { "type": "proxy", "target": "https://example.com" }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "backgroundTasks": [
    {
      "command": "tsc",
      "arguments": ["-w"]
    }
  ],
  "mime": ["foo=application/x-foo"]
}
.Ed
.Pp
The structure of the document
.Pq with all default values shown
is:
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "servers": [
    {
      "port": <port number>,
      "host": "localhost",
      "options": {
        "requestTimeout": 300000,
        "keepAliveTimeout": 5000,
        "keepAliveTimeoutBuffer": 1000,
        "connectionsCheckingInterval": 30000,
        "headersTimeout": 60000,
        "highWaterMark": 65536,
        "maxHeaderSize": 16384,
        "noDelay": true,
        "requireHostHeader": true,
        "keepAlive": false,
        "keepAliveInitialDelay": 0,
        "uniqueHeaders": <array of header names>,
        "backlog": 511,
        "socketTimeout": 6000,
        "rejectNonStandardExpect": false,
        "autoContinue": false,
        "logRequests": true,
        "restartTimeout": 2000,
        "shutdownTimeout": 500
      },
      "mount": <array of mounts>
    }
  ],
  "backgroundTasks": [
    {
      "command": <name of command or path to executable>,
      "arguments": [],
      "cwd": ".",
      "environment": {},
      "options": {
        "uid": <user ID number>,
        "gid": <group ID number>,
        "killSignal": "SIGTERM",
        "displayStdout": true,
        "displayStderr": true
      }
    }
  ],
  "mime": <array of mime definitions>,
  "writeCompressed": false,
  "minCompress": 300,
  "noServe": false,
  "log": "progress"
}
.Ed
.Pp
Within each server,
.Qq mount
defines an ordered list of services
.Pq "earlier definitions take priority over later definitions" .
.Pp
The available mount types are:
.Bl -tag -width 2n
.
.It Qq files
Serve files from a directory.
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "type": "files",
  "path": "/",
  "dir": ".",
  "options": {
    "mode": "dynamic",
    "fallback": {
      "statusCode": 200,
      "filePath": <path to fallback file>
    },
    "headers": {},
    "verbose": false,
    "subDirectories": true,
    "caseSensitive": "exact",
    "allowAllDotfiles": false,
    "allowAllTildefiles": false,
    "allowDirectIndexAccess": false,
    "hide": [],
    "allow": [".well-known"],
    "indexFiles": ["index.htm", "index.html"],
    "implicitSuffixes": [],
    "negotiation": []
  }
}
.Ed
.
.It Qq fixture
Serve a fixture.
May include templates in headers and body.
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "type": "fixture",
  "path": <path>,
  "method": "GET",
  "status": 200,
  "headers": {},
  "body": <fixture content>
}
.Ed
.
.It Qq redirect
Serve a redirect.
May include templates in target.
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "type": "redirect",
  "path": <path>,
  "status": 307,
  "target": <target URL>
}
.Ed
.
.It Qq proxy
Proxy requests to another server.
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "type": "proxy",
  "path": "/",
  "target": <target URL>
  "options": {
    "noDelay": false,
    "keepAlive": false,
    "keepAliveInitialDelay": <number>,
    "keepAliveMsecs": <number>,
    "agentKeepAliveTimeoutBuffer": <number>,
    "maxSockets": <number>,
    "maxFreeSockets": <number>,
    "timeout": <number>,
    "headers": {},
    "blockRequestHeaders": [],
    "blockResponseHeaders": [],
    "servername": <string>,
    "ca": <string>,
    "cert": <string>,
    "sigalgs": <string>,
    "ciphers": <string>,
    "crl": <string>,
    "ecdhCurve": <string>,
    "key": <string>,
    "passphrase": <string>,
    "pfx": <string>,
    "sessionTimeout": <number>,
    "maxCachedSessions": <number>
  }
}
.Ed
.
.El
.Pp
Templates behave like Javascript templates, using the
.Qq ${variable}
syntax.
The available variables are:
.Bl -bullet
.It
path parameter names
.Po
as shown in the example above:
.Qq "${thepath}"
.Pc ,
.It
named query / search parameters
.Po
with
.Qq "${?parameter}"
.Pc ,
.It
the entire query / search part of the request
.Po
with
.Qq "${?}"
.Pc .
.El
.Pp
Templates are mostly useful for creating dynamic redirects as shown above, but
can also be used in the
.Qq body
and
.Qq header
values for
.Qq fixture
definitions.
.Pp
To specify a fallback value, use the shell-style
.Qq ":-" :
.Qq "${pathParameter:-fallback}"
.Pp
Redirects automatically uri-encode parameters as needed for convenience
.Po
but you can override this by explicitly specifying
.Fn raw
or
.Fn uri
encoding
.Pc .
Other templates do not apply any encoding by default.
To apply encoding, specify the type you need:
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
{
  "servers": [
    {
      "port": 8080,
      "mount": [
        {
          "type": "fixture",
          "method": "GET",
          "path": "/*path.htm",
          "status": 200,
          "body": "<html><body><h1>You requested ${html(path)}!</h1><p>You also added: ${html(?):-<em>no query string</em>}</p></body></html>"
        },
        {
          "type": "fixture",
          "method": "GET",
          "path": "/*path.json",
          "status": 200,
          "body": "{\e"path\e":${json(path)},\e"page\e":${int(?page:-1)}}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
.Ed
.Pp
The available encoding types are:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fn raw
the original value, unmodified
.Pq path and query parameters will be URL decoded
.It Fn html
the value with special HTML characters escaped using
.Qq "&"
escapes
.It Fn json
the value as a JSON string
.Pq even if it could be represented as a number, it will be encoded as a string
.It Fn int
the value as a plain integer, safe to include in HTML, JSON, URIs, etc.
.Po
prints
.Qq 0
if the input is not a valid integer
.Pc
.It Fn uri
the value mapped through
.Fn encodeURIComponent
.Po
for multi-component path parameters, each component is encoded individually
then joined with
.Qq "/"
.Pc .
This is the default encoding when writing redirects, except for
.Qq "${?}"
which is encoded
.Fn raw
by default.
.El
.Pp
Note that this template language is designed to serve common needs for simple
templating, such as redirects and simple testing stubs; it is not intended to
be comprehensive.
If you have more demanding needs you should use a dedicated templating library
and build an application, rather than configuring endpoints using the CLI.
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh MIME DEFINITIONS
When defining mime types, some shorthands are available:
.Bl -bullet
.It
multiple mappings separated by semicolons:
.Qq foo=text/x-foo;bar=text/x-bar
.It
multiple file extensions separated by commas:
.Qq foo,bar=text/plain
.It
use the file extension in the mime type with {ext}:
.Qq css,csv=text/{ext}
.It
optional parts in brackets:
.Qq jp(e)g,tif(f)=image/{ext}
.Po
{ext} always maps to the full name, so the example maps
.Qq *.jpg
to
.Qq image/jpeg
.Pc
.El
.Pp
When using an apache .types file, each line contains a mime type, any amount of
whitespace, then a list of space-separated extensions
.Pq "without a dot" .
Lines starting with
.Qq #
are ignored as comments.
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh EXIT STATUS
The
.Nm
program exits 0 after a clean shutdown, and non-zero after an error
.Pq "such as a configuration validation error, or a port already in use" .
.
.\"======================================================================
.Sh EXAMPLES
Serve files from the current working directory on
.Lk "http://localhost:3000" :
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --port 3000"
.Pp
Bind to all addresses, so the server is available over the network:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --host 0.0.0.0 --port 3000"
.Pp
Add custom mime types:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --mime 'foo=text/x-foo' --mime 'bar=text/x-bar'"
.Pp
Proxy all requests to another server:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener /dev/null --proxy https://example.com"
.Pp
Add security headers to enable browser secure context:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . -H 'Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin' -H 'Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy: require-corp'"
.Pp
Enable compressed files, and auto-generate them on startup:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --brotli --gzip --write-compressed --min-compress 500"
.Pp
Run the TypeScript compiler in watch mode while serving files:
.Pp
.Dl "$ npx web-listener . --exec 'tsc -w'"
.Pp
Using inline JSON configuration:
.Pp
.Dl $ npx web-listener --config-json '{"servers":[{"port":8080,"mount":[{"type":"files","path":"/","dir":".","options":{"fallback":{"filePath":"index.html"}}}]}]}'
.
